activityormissiondesc: To promote the well-being of Asian Pacific American youth and families. See Part III
desc: DC Elementary School Program: AALEAD provides high quality academic enrichment programs at two DC Elementary, Bancroft ES and Thomson ES, and in FY14 provided a full-day five-week summer program which served 75 students at Thomson ES. Our program components include, but are not limited to, homework help, field trips, and enrichment activities focused on exploring culture and identity, building leadership skills, and completing community service. Past enrichment activities and field trips have included "country studies" where students spend time examining different aspects of a region's culture, lessons on developing and practicing leadership skills, and discussions of career goals. Field trips have included taking part in a park clean-up and participating in Fiesta Asia, an annual street festival celebrating Asian and Asian Pacific Islander cultures. In FY14, 100% of our Elementary School students passed on to the next grade level.

missiondesc: AALEAD supports low-income and underserved Asian Pacific American youth with educational empowerment, identity development, and leadership opportunities through after school, summer, and mentoring programs. Vision: AALEAD envisions a United States in which low-income and underserved Asian Pacific American youth, and youth of all backgrounds, are equipped with the tools and opportunities to define themselves and their own futures.

activityormissiondesc: Sitar Arts Center advances the critical life skills of underserved children and youth in Washington, DC and prepares them for achievement in the 21st century through visual, performing, and digital arts education in a nurturing community. During 2013, Sitar Arts Center served 798 students. True to its mission, Sitar has maintained its policy that 80% of students are from low-income households.
desc: Visual artsThrough the visual arts program at Sitar Arts Center, students discover a new means of self-expression while gaining skills in a wide range of artistic mediums as well as 21st century life skills such as creative and critical thinking and communication. In the Early Childhood Arts program, preschoolers explore a variety of art forms with their parents, creating an ideal environment for parent and child engagement. In Arts Afterschool, school-aged students choose from 30 different classes including studio art, pottery, dark-room photography, fiber arts, sewing and fashion design, mosaics and more. At Camp Sitar, elementary students have six weeks of daily arts classes and teens enroll in the twice weekly teen intensive. The summer teen intern visual artists are commissioned by corporate and nonprofit organizations to paint large scale murals to install on their buildings.

missiondesc: Sitar Arts Center bridges an opportunity gap in Washington DC by providing an arts education that positively impacts youth from low-income households. Sitar's programs serve as an essential vehicle for devloping the 21st century educational and workforce skills tha pave the way for lasting achievement. Sitar's primary focus is reaching families that would not otherwise have these opportunities. 80% of Sitar's students are from low-income households. Alongside its students and families, Sitar collaboratively builds an engaging and supportive community that brings together the District's families, teaching artists, and cultural partners.

activityormissiondesc: The Fishing School prepares public school elementary and middle school youth for success in high school and life by improving their academic performance and life skills; engaging them and their parents in intensive, multi- year, and research-based out-of-school time and parental engagement programs and activities.
desc: AFTER-SCHOOL & PARENT SUPPORT PROGRAMS: TFS' AFTERSCHOOL PROGRAM IS AN OUT OF SCHOOL TIME PROGRAM WHERE INSTRUCTORS WORK WITH PARTICIPANTS TO IMPROVE THEIR ACADEMIC AND LIFE SKILLS, DEVELOPING THEIR ABILITY TO ATTAIN PERSONAL GOALS. THE PROGRAM INCLUDES MANY UNIQUE FEATURES, SUCH AS STEAM (SCIENCE, TECHNOLOGY, ENGINEERING, ARTS, AND MATH) ACTIVITIES TO HELP PARTICIPANTS APPLY MATH AND READING CONCEPTS, BUILD EXPOSURE TO THE SCIENCES, AND DEVELOP CRITICAL THINKING SKILLS. IN ADDITION, YOUTH USE A COMPUTER-BASED DIAGNOSTIC AND TUTORING CURRICULUM AND OTHER VIRTUAL TOOLS TO FURTHER SUPPORT THEIR ACADEMIC DEVELOPMENT. THE AFTERSCHOOL PROGRAM OPERATES DURING THE ACADEMIC SCHOOL YEAR FROM SEPTEMBER TO JUNE, FROM 3:30 PM TO 6:00 PM IN LOCAL SCHOOLS THROUGH A FORMAL PARTNERSHIP WITH THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA PUBLIC SCHOOL SYSTEM. PARENTS OF TFS YOUTH PARTICIPATE IN YEAR ROUND PARENT SUPPORT AND ENGAGEMENT ACTIVITIES AND EVENTS DESIGNED TO INCREASE PARENTS' AND CAREGIVERS' KNOWLEDGE AND SKILLS OF YOUTH DEVELOPMENT AND EMPOWER THEM TO MAKE USE OF BEST PRACTICES. TFS CONNECTS WITH PARENTS THROUGH FAMILY EVENTS, ADVISORY COMMITTEES, NEWSLETTERS, REGULAR PROGRESS REPORTS, REFERRALS, AND EXPERT GUIDANCE FROM EXTERNAL PARTNERS.

activityormissiondesc: CITYDANCE IS A RECOGNIZED ARTS AND EDUCATION LEADER IN OUR NATION'S CAPITAL. FOUNDED IN 1996, CITYDANCE'S MISSION IS TO BRING THE HIGHEST- QUALITY PROFESSIONAL DANCE TO D.C. STAGES; TRAIN YOUTH FOR 21ST CENTURY DANCE CAREERS; AND PROVIDE ACCESS TO DANCE TRAINING AND PERFORMANCE TO UNDERSERVED POPULATIONS.
desc: CITYDANCE IS A RECOGNIZED ARTS AND EDUCATION LEADER IN OUR NATION'S CAPITAL. FOUNDED IN 1996, CITYDANCE'S MISSION IS TO BRING THE HIGHEST- QUALITY PROFESSIONAL DANCE TO D.C. STAGES; TRAIN YOUTH FOR 21ST CENTURY DANCE CAREERS; AND PROVIDE ACCESS TO DANCE TRAINING AND PERFORMANCE TO UNDERSERVED POPULATIONS. CITYDANCE ONSTAGE CITYDANCE ONSTAGE PRESENTS NATIONAL AND INTERNATIONAL COMPANIES AT THE REGION'S MOST PRESTIGIOUS PERFORMANCE VENUES; SUPPORTS EMERGING CHOREOGRAPHERS, LOCAL AND BEYOND; AND PROVIDES UNPARALLELED OPPORTUNITIES FOR OUR STUDENTS TO WORK AND PERFORM WITH PROFESSIONAL ARTISTS. FOLLOWING A SUCCESSFUL PILOT PARTNERSHIP WITH WASHINGTON PERFORMING ARTS IN THE SPRING OF 2013, THE PARTNERSHIP WAS EXPANDED TO CO-PRESENT A FULL SEASON OF DANCE AT PROMINENT METRO-AREA VENUES. THE 2013-2014 SEASON BEGAN WITH A PERFORMANCE BY RENOWNED DANCE THEATRE OF HARLEM (DTH) AT SYDNEY HARMAN HALL OCTOBER 17-19 THAT FEATURED SEVEN CITYDANCE SCHOOL & CONSERVATORY STUDENTS. PRIOR TO THE PERFORMANCE, DTH ARTISTIC DIRECTOR VIRGINIA JOHNSON TAUGHT THREE MASTER DANCE CLASSES TO 75 SCHOOL & CONSERVATORY STUDENTS AGES 9-19. DUE TO THE OVERWHELMING RESPONSE BY OUR STUDENTS AND THE COMMUNITY, CITYDANCE AND DTH ESTABLISHED A CONTINUED PARTNERSHIP THAT RESULTED IN DTH HOSTING ITS SUMMER BALLET INTENSIVE AT OUR SCHOOL & CONSERVATORY JUNE 22 - JULY 3. CITYDANCE AND WPAS PARTNERED TWICE MORE IN THE SEASON TO PRESENT KORESH DANCE COMPANY AND MOMIX. KORESH DANCE COMPANY ARTISTIC DIRECTOR MELISSA RECTOR SPENT FIVE DAYS AT THE CITYDANCE SCHOOL & CONSERVATORY SETTING THE COMPANY'S WORK "STANDING IN TEARS" ON 15 CONSERVATORY STUDENTS WHICH WAS PERFORMED AS THE OPENING PIECE FOR BOTH KORESH PERFORMANCES. CITYDANCE ALSO BRINGS RENOWNED ARTISTS TO THE DC AREA THROUGH OUR ANNUAL GALA, WHICH RAISES FUNDS TO SUPPORT OUR CORNERSTONE COMMUNITY PROGRAM, DREAM. CO-PRODUCED BY RENOWNED DANCER AND PRODUCER RASTA THOMAS, THE EVENING BRINGS DANCE SUPERSTARS FROM AROUND THE WORLD FOR ONE NIGHT OF SPECTACULAR DANCE AT DC'S LINCOLN THEATRE. IN ADDITION TO PRESENTING NATIONALLY-RENOWNED ARTISTS THROUGH CITYDANCE ONSTAGE, WE ALSO PRESENT LOCAL ARTISTS THROUGH CITYDANCE IGNITE. THE PROGRAM SUPPORTS EMERGING DANCE ARTISTS IN THE CREATION AND PERFORMANCE OF THEIR WORK BY PROVIDING THEM WITH REHEARSAL SPACE IN THE SPACIOUS STUDIOS AT THE CITYDANCE CENTER AT STRATHMORE; THE ABILITY TO PRESENT THEIR ORIGINAL WORK IN THE STATE-OF-THE-ART CITYDANCE STUDIO THEATER AT STRATHMORE; AND MARKETING, PR, AND ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT FROM CITYDANCE STAFF. RESIDENT ARTISTS INCLUDED ROBERT J. PRIORE, ASANGA DOMASK, AND SARA J. EWING. IN JANUARY, WE PRESENTED THE FIRST OF THESE ARTISTS, ROBERT J. PRIORE, DURING TWO SOLD-OUT PERFORMANCES IN THE STUDIO THEATER. THE COMPELLING PROGRAM FEATURED GUEST ARTISTS FROM DAYTON CONTEMPORARY DANCE COMPANY PERFORMING PRIORE'S NEWEST WORK, AN ORIGINAL WORK SET ON CONSERVATORY STUDENTS, AND A THIRD WORK FEATURING CONSERVATORY STUDENTS ALONGSIDE PROFESSIONAL DANCERS. IN MARCH RESIDENT ARTIST ASANGA DOMASK, AN INTERNATIONALLY-RECOGNIZED SRI LANKAN TRADITIONAL AND FOLK DANCE PERFORMER WHO DIRECTS CITYDANCE'S SRI LANKAN DANCE PROGRAM, PARTNERED WITH MARYLAND CLASSICAL YOUTH ORCHESTRAS AND CITYDANCE STUDENTS TO PERFORM INTERPRETATIONS OF THE ICONIC SWANS FROM "SWAN LAKE." IN APRIL, RESIDENT ARTIST SARA J. EWING PREMIERED HER FULL-LENGTH WORK, TRAPPED HAPPINESS, IN THE CITYDANCE STUDIO THEATER. CITYDANCE COMMUNITY PROGRAMS SERVING UNDER-RESOURCED YOUTH IN WASHINGTON DC FOR NEARLY TWO DECADES, CITYDANCE'S COMMUNITY PROGRAMS HAVE DEVELOPED A STRONG REPUTATION FOR ENGAGING AND EMPOWERING YOUNG PEOPLE. THROUGH TWO DISTINCTIVE PROGRAMS, DREAM AND REACHDC, CITYDANCE COMMUNITY PROGRAMS ARE OFFERED AT OVER 30 COMMUNITY-BASED SITES IN THE REGION'S MOST UNDER-RESOURCED NEIGHBORHOODS PROVIDING FREE PERFORMANCES, IN-SCHOOL AND AFTER-SCHOOL PROGRAMS, AND SUMMER CAMPS TO OVER 5,000 STUDENTS EACH YEAR. DREAM AS THE ARTS BECOME LESS ACCESSIBLE IN OUR SCHOOLS, DREAM REACHES INTO OUR NEIGHBORHOODS, GIVING BACK TO OUR STUDENTS WHAT IS FUNDAMENTAL TO ANY CHILD'S FUTURE - EXPERIENCE AND PARTICIPATION IN THE ARTS. NOW IN ITS TENTH YEAR, THE FOUR-HOUR A WEEK AFTER-SCHOOL PROGRAM IS OFFERED TO 120 STUDENTS IN THIRD THROUGH EIGHTH GRADES AT SIX DC PUBLIC SCHOOLS AND EMPLOYS THE PRINCIPLES OF ADVANCING YOUTH DEVELOPMENT - A NATIONALLY-RECOGNIZED MODEL FOR INSTILLING YOUTH WITH THE SKILLS NECESSARY FOR SUCCESS IN LIFE. THE DREAM CURRICULUM IS DESIGNED TO ACHIEVE THREE SPECIFIC AYD GOALS: MASTERY AND FUTURE - STUDENTS DEVELOP A SENSE OF COMPETENCY AND THE BELIEF THEY CAN CREATE SUCCESS IN THEIR LIVES; BELONGING AND MEMBERSHIP - STUDENTS LEARN TO FORM MEANINGFUL CONNECTIONS AND RELATIONSHIPS WITH PEERS AND ADULTS; AND CIVIC AND SOCIAL ABILITY - STUDENTS LEARN HOW TO WORK COLLABORATIVELY TO SUCCESSFULLY REACH A GOAL AND BELIEVE IN THEIR ABILITY TO HAVE AN IMPACT ON THEIR COMMUNITY AND SURROUNDINGS. CITYDANCE SEEKS TO ACHIEVE THESE GOALS THROUGH THE FOLLOWING ACTIVITIES: "DANCE INSTRUCTION: STUDENTS LEARN THE TECHNIQUE, HISTORY AND EVOLUTION OF A VARIETY OF DANCE FORMS. "COMMUNITY SERVICE: STUDENTS CHOOSE A COMMUNITY SERVICE PROJECT BY IDENTIFYING A COMMUNITY CONCERN AND CHOREOGRAPHING A DANCE TO ADDRESS THE CONCERN (E.G., HEALTHY EATING OR ANTI-DRUG CAMPAIGNS). "CREATIVE WRITING: THROUGH WEEKLY JOURNALING AND A PEN PAL PROGRAM WITH DREAM PARTICIPANTS AT DIFFERENT SCHOOLS, STUDENTS BUILD POSITIVE RELATIONSHIPS WITH PEERS AND HONE THEIR WRITING SKILLS. "DREAM PERFORMANCE REHEARSALS: DURING GROUP REHEARSALS WITH ALL DREAM PARTICIPANTS, STUDENTS LEARN THE VALUE OF TEAMWORK AND BRIDGING DIFFERENCES WHILE PRACTICING FOR THEIR MID-YEAR PERFORMANCE. "WIZARDS PERFORMANCE: STUDENTS PERFORM AT A WASHINGTON WIZARDS HALF-TIME SHOW AT THE VERIZON CENTER, EXPERIENCING THE THRILL OF PERFORMING FOR THE MORE THAN 20,000 PEOPLE IN ATTENDANCE. "ALL-SCHOOL ANNUAL PERFORMANCE: STUDENTS PERFORM IN A PROFESSIONAL THEATER FOR PARENTS AND COMMUNITY MEMBERS, SHOWCASING THEIR DANCE SKILLS AND THE COMMUNITY SERVICE PROJECTS THEY WORKED ON DURING THE YEAR. "CULMINATING COMMUNITY PERFORMANCE: EACH DREAM SCHOOL HOSTS ITS OWN YEAR- END PERFORMANCE AT A VENUE RELEVANT TO THEIR COMMUNITY GOAL. WE ASSESS DREAM THROUGH FORMAL EVALUATION TOOLS DEVELOPED BY EXTERNAL EVALUATORS IN 2011 THAT UTILIZE QUALITATIVE AND QUANTITATIVE ASSESSMENT TOOLS SUCH AS FOCUS GROUPS, PRE- AND POST-TEST SKILLS ASSESSMENT SURVEYS FROM TEACHERS, AND PRE- AND POST-TEST SELF- ASSESSMENT SURVEYS. IN 2014, THESE SAME EVALUATORS REVIEWED DREAM AND CREATED NEW EVALUATION TOOLS THAT CAN BE USED BY CITYDANCE STAFF FOR YEARS TO COME, YOUTH SELF-ASSESSMENT TOOLS, KNOWLEDGE SURVEYS AND YEAR-END FEEDBACK SURVEYS. DUE TO HOW PROFOUNDLY DREAM CONSISTENTLY IMPACTS THE DC PUBLIC SCHOOL STUDENTS WE SERVE, WE BECAME DETERMINED TO DEEPEN AND LENGTHEN OUR RELATIONSHIP WITH THESE YOUTH. IN 2010, WE BEGAN OFFERING CONTINUED SERVICES TO STUDENTS FROM SIXTH GRADE THROUGH HIGH SCHOOL THROUGH OUR DREAM ALUMNI PROGRAM. TODAY, CITYDANCE SERVES 34 STUDENTS THROUGH THE PROGRAM GIVING THEM FREE DANCE INSTRUCTION FOR TWO HOURS EACH WEEK SEPTEMBER THROUGH MAY BUILD UPON THE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PRINCIPLES THAT SERVE AS THE CORNERSTONE OF THE DREAM CURRICULUM. ADDITIONALLY, WE PROVIDE ALUMNI WITH THE OPPORTUNITY TO SEE PROFESSIONAL DANCE PERFORMANCES FREE OF CHARGE, PERFORM ALONGSIDE DREAM STUDENTS AND IN THEIR OWN SHOWS, ACADEMIC TUTORING, THE OPTION TO MENTOR DREAM STUDENTS, AND HELP WITH COLLEGE PLANNING AND PREPARATION. REACHDC THROUGH PARTNERSHIPS WITH ORGANIZATIONS THROUGHOUT THE METROPOLITAN AREA, REACHDC EXPANDS CITYDANCE'S CONNECTION TO THE LARGER COMMUNITY. PROGRAMMING RANGES FROM PERFORMANCES IN A VAST ARRAY OF GENRES TO ARTS-INTEGRATION RESIDENCIES, SUMMER CAMPS, AFTER-SCHOOL PROGRAMS, AND FIELD-TRIPS. REACHDC PARTNERS INCLUDE: BOYS AND GIRLS CLUB, DC DEPARTMENT OF PARKS AND RECREATION, DC PUBLIC SCHOOLS, DEA YOUTH DANCE PROGRAM, KIPP DC CHARTER SCHOOLS, MONTGOMERY COUNTY DEPARTMENT OF RECREATION, THE SITAR ARTS CENTER, SPRINGBOARD AFTER SCHOOL, AND WASHINGTON PERFORMING ARTS SOCIETY. REACH DC PROVIDED THE FOLLOWING DANCE EDUCATION PROGRAMMING AND FREE PERFORMANCES: -CITYDANCE WILL HELD FREE PROFESSIONAL "DANCING IN ONE LANGUAGE" PERFORMANCES FOR OVER 1,500 STUDENTS ACROSS THE DC-METRO AREA. -SUMMER CAMPS: STEEPED IN THE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PHILOSOPHY, CITYDANCE'S DANCING AROUND THE WORLD SUMMER CAMPS PROVIDED SAFETY AND STRUCTURE FOR OVER 400 YOUTH. CAMPS WERE OFFERED TO YOUTH AGES 5 -14, FROM 4-8 WEEKS FOR SEVERAL HOURS A DAY AT SEVERAL COMMUNITY-BASED SITES, INCLUDING THE KIPP DC SCHOOLS, YMCA, THE BOYS AND GIRLS CLUB AND FOUR MARYLAND-BASED RECREATION CENTERS THROUGH A PARTNERSHIP WITH THE COMMONWEAL FOUNDATION. -AFTER-SCHOOL PARTNERSHIPS: THROUGH LONG-STANDING PARTNERSHIPS, CITYDANCE BRINGS DANCE INSTRUCTION TO COMMUNITY-BASED SITES AND SCHOOLS, PROVIDING WEEKLY INSTRUCTION IN A VARIETY OF GENRES TO OVER 200 STUDENTS. IN 2014, THESE SAME EVALUATORS REVIEWED DREAM AND CREATED NEW EVALUATION TOOLS THAT CAN BE USED BY CITYDANCE STAFF FOR YEARS TO COME, YOUTH SELF-ASSESSMENT TOOLS, KNOWLEDGE SURVEYS AND YEAR-END FEEDBACK SURVEYS. DUE TO HOW PROFOUNDLY DREAM CONSISTENTLY IMPACTS THE DC PUBLIC SCHOOL STUDENTS WE SERVE, WE BECAME DETERMINED TO DEEPEN AND LENGTHEN OUR RELATIONSHIP WITH THESE YOUTH. IN 2010, WE BEGAN OFFERING CONTINUED SERVICES TO STUDENTS FROM SIXTH GRADE THROUGH HIGH SCHOOL THROUGH OUR DREAM ALUMNI PROGRAM. TODAY, CITYDANCE SERVES 34 STUDENTS THROUGH THE PROGRAM GIVING THEM FREE DANCE INSTRUCTION FOR TWO HOURS EACH WEEK SEPTEMBER THROUGH MAY BUILD UPON THE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PRINCIPLES THAT SERVE AS THE CORNERSTONE OF THE DREAM CURRICULUM. ADDITIONALLY, WE PROVIDE ALUMNI WITH THE OPPORTUNITY TO SEE PROFESSIONAL DANCE PERFORMANCES FREE OF CHARGE, PERFORM ALONGSIDE DREAM STUDENTS AND IN THEIR OWN SHOWS, ACADEMIC TUTORING, THE OPTION TO MENTOR DREAM STUDENTS, AND HELP WITH COLLEGE PLANNING AND PREPARATION. REACHDC THROUGH PARTNERSHIPS WITH ORGANIZATIONS THROUGHOUT THE METROPOLITAN AREA, REACHDC EXPANDS CITYDANCE'S CONNECTION TO THE LARGER COMMUNITY. PROGRAMMING RANGES FROM PERFORMANCES IN A VAST ARRAY OF GENRES TO ARTS-INTEGRATION RESIDENCIES, SUMMER CAMPS, AFTER-SCHOOL PROGRAMS, AND FIELD-TRIPS. REACHDC PARTNERS INCLUDE: BOYS AND GIRLS CLUB, DC DEPARTMENT OF PARKS AND RECREATION, DC PUBLIC SCHOOLS, DEA YOUTH DANCE PROGRAM, KIPP DC CHARTER SCHOOLS, MONTGOMERY COUNTY DEPARTMENT OF RECREATION, THE SITAR ARTS CENTER, SPRINGBOARD AFTER SCHOOL, AND WASHINGTON PERFORMING ARTS SOCIETY. REACH DC PROVIDED THE FOLLOWING DANCE EDUCATION PROGRAMMING AND FREE PERFORMANCES: -CITYDANCE WILL HELD FREE PROFESSIONAL "DANCING IN ONE LANGUAGE" PERFORMANCES FOR OVER 1,500 STUDENTS ACROSS THE DC-METRO AREA. -SUMMER CAMPS: STEEPED IN THE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PHILOSOPHY, CITYDANCE'S DANCING AROUND THE WORLD SUMMER CAMPS PROVIDED SAFETY AND STRUCTURE FOR OVER 400 YOUTH. CAMPS WERE OFFERED TO YOUTH AGES 5 -14, FROM 4-8 WEEKS FOR SEVERAL HOURS A DAY AT SEVERAL COMMUNITY-BASED SITES, INCLUDING THE KIPP DC SCHOOLS, YMCA, THE BOYS AND GIRLS CLUB AND FOUR MARYLAND-BASED RECREATION CENTERS THROUGH A PARTNERSHIP WITH THE COMMONWEAL FOUNDATION. -AFTER-SCHOOL PARTNERSHIPS: THROUGH LONG-STANDING PARTNERSHIPS, CITYDANCE BRINGS DANCE INSTRUCTION TO COMMUNITY-BASED SITES AND SCHOOLS, PROVIDING WEEKLY INSTRUCTION IN A VARIETY OF GENRES TO OVER 200 STUDENTS. desc.2: CITYDANCE IS A RECOGNIZED ARTS AND EDUCATION LEADER IN OUR NATION'S CAPITAL. FOUNDED IN 1996, CITYDANCE'S MISSION IS TO BRING THE HIGHEST- QUALITY PROFESSIONAL DANCE TO D.C. STAGES; TRAIN YOUTH FOR 21ST CENTURY DANCE CAREERS; AND PROVIDE ACCESS TO DANCE TRAINING AND PERFORMANCE TO UNDERSERVED POPULATIONS. CITYDANCE ONSTAGE CITYDANCE ONSTAGE PRESENTS NATIONAL AND INTERNATIONAL COMPANIES AT THE REGION'S MOST PRESTIGIOUS PERFORMANCE VENUES; SUPPORTS EMERGING CHOREOGRAPHERS, LOCAL AND BEYOND; AND PROVIDES UNPARALLELED OPPORTUNITIES FOR OUR STUDENTS TO WORK AND PERFORM WITH PROFESSIONAL ARTISTS. FOLLOWING A SUCCESSFUL PILOT PARTNERSHIP WITH WASHINGTON PERFORMING ARTS IN THE SPRING OF 2013, THE PARTNERSHIP WAS EXPANDED TO CO-PRESENT A FULL SEASON OF DANCE AT PROMINENT METRO-AREA VENUES. THE 2013-2014 SEASON BEGAN WITH A PERFORMANCE BY RENOWNED DANCE THEATRE OF HARLEM (DTH) AT SYDNEY HARMAN HALL OCTOBER 17-19 THAT FEATURED SEVEN CITYDANCE SCHOOL & CONSERVATORY STUDENTS. PRIOR TO THE PERFORMANCE, DTH ARTISTIC DIRECTOR VIRGINIA JOHNSON TAUGHT THREE MASTER DANCE CLASSES TO 75 SCHOOL & CONSERVATORY STUDENTS AGES 9-19. DUE TO THE OVERWHELMING RESPONSE BY OUR STUDENTS AND THE COMMUNITY, CITYDANCE AND DTH ESTABLISHED A CONTINUED PARTNERSHIP THAT RESULTED IN DTH HOSTING ITS SUMMER BALLET INTENSIVE AT OUR SCHOOL & CONSERVATORY JUNE 22 - JULY 3. CITYDANCE AND WPAS PARTNERED TWICE MORE IN THE SEASON TO PRESENT KORESH DANCE COMPANY AND MOMIX. KORESH DANCE COMPANY ARTISTIC DIRECTOR MELISSA RECTOR SPENT FIVE DAYS AT THE CITYDANCE SCHOOL & CONSERVATORY SETTING THE COMPANY'S WORK "STANDING IN TEARS" ON 15 CONSERVATORY STUDENTS WHICH WAS PERFORMED AS THE OPENING PIECE FOR BOTH KORESH PERFORMANCES. CITYDANCE ALSO BRINGS RENOWNED ARTISTS TO THE DC AREA THROUGH OUR ANNUAL GALA, WHICH RAISES FUNDS TO SUPPORT OUR CORNERSTONE COMMUNITY PROGRAM, DREAM. CO-PRODUCED BY RENOWNED DANCER AND PRODUCER RASTA THOMAS, THE EVENING BRINGS DANCE SUPERSTARS FROM AROUND THE WORLD FOR ONE NIGHT OF SPECTACULAR DANCE AT DC'S LINCOLN THEATRE. IN ADDITION TO PRESENTING NATIONALLY-RENOWNED ARTISTS THROUGH CITYDANCE ONSTAGE, WE ALSO PRESENT LOCAL ARTISTS THROUGH CITYDANCE IGNITE. THE PROGRAM SUPPORTS EMERGING DANCE ARTISTS IN THE CREATION AND PERFORMANCE OF THEIR WORK BY PROVIDING THEM WITH REHEARSAL SPACE IN THE SPACIOUS STUDIOS AT THE CITYDANCE CENTER AT STRATHMORE; THE ABILITY TO PRESENT THEIR ORIGINAL WORK IN THE STATE-OF-THE-ART CITYDANCE STUDIO THEATER AT STRATHMORE; AND MARKETING, PR, AND ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT FROM CITYDANCE STAFF. RESIDENT ARTISTS INCLUDED ROBERT J. PRIORE, ASANGA DOMASK, AND SARA J. EWING. IN JANUARY, WE PRESENTED THE FIRST OF THESE ARTISTS, ROBERT J. PRIORE, DURING TWO SOLD-OUT PERFORMANCES IN THE STUDIO THEATER. THE COMPELLING PROGRAM FEATURED GUEST ARTISTS FROM DAYTON CONTEMPORARY DANCE COMPANY PERFORMING PRIORE'S NEWEST WORK, AN ORIGINAL WORK SET ON CONSERVATORY STUDENTS, AND A THIRD WORK FEATURING CONSERVATORY STUDENTS ALONGSIDE PROFESSIONAL DANCERS. IN MARCH RESIDENT ARTIST ASANGA DOMASK, AN INTERNATIONALLY-RECOGNIZED SRI LANKAN TRADITIONAL AND FOLK DANCE PERFORMER WHO DIRECTS CITYDANCE'S SRI LANKAN DANCE PROGRAM, PARTNERED WITH MARYLAND CLASSICAL YOUTH ORCHESTRAS AND CITYDANCE STUDENTS TO PERFORM INTERPRETATIONS OF THE ICONIC SWANS FROM "SWAN LAKE." IN APRIL, RESIDENT ARTIST SARA J. EWING PREMIERED HER FULL-LENGTH WORK, TRAPPED HAPPINESS, IN THE CITYDANCE STUDIO THEATER. CITYDANCE COMMUNITY PROGRAMS SERVING UNDER-RESOURCED YOUTH IN WASHINGTON DC FOR NEARLY TWO DECADES, CITYDANCE'S COMMUNITY PROGRAMS HAVE DEVELOPED A STRONG REPUTATION FOR ENGAGING AND EMPOWERING YOUNG PEOPLE. THROUGH TWO DISTINCTIVE PROGRAMS, DREAM AND REACHDC, CITYDANCE COMMUNITY PROGRAMS ARE OFFERED AT OVER 30 COMMUNITY-BASED SITES IN THE REGION'S MOST UNDER-RESOURCED NEIGHBORHOODS PROVIDING FREE PERFORMANCES, IN-SCHOOL AND AFTER-SCHOOL PROGRAMS, AND SUMMER CAMPS TO OVER 5,000 STUDENTS EACH YEAR. DREAM AS THE ARTS BECOME LESS ACCESSIBLE IN OUR SCHOOLS, DREAM REACHES INTO OUR NEIGHBORHOODS, GIVING BACK TO OUR STUDENTS WHAT IS FUNDAMENTAL TO ANY CHILD'S FUTURE - EXPERIENCE AND PARTICIPATION IN THE ARTS. NOW IN ITS TENTH YEAR, THE FOUR-HOUR A WEEK AFTER-SCHOOL PROGRAM IS OFFERED TO 120 STUDENTS IN THIRD THROUGH EIGHTH GRADES AT SIX DC PUBLIC SCHOOLS AND EMPLOYS THE PRINCIPLES OF ADVANCING YOUTH DEVELOPMENT - A NATIONALLY-RECOGNIZED MODEL FOR INSTILLING YOUTH WITH THE SKILLS NECESSARY FOR SUCCESS IN LIFE. THE DREAM CURRICULUM IS DESIGNED TO ACHIEVE THREE SPECIFIC AYD GOALS: MASTERY AND FUTURE - STUDENTS DEVELOP A SENSE OF COMPETENCY AND THE BELIEF THEY CAN CREATE SUCCESS IN THEIR LIVES; BELONGING AND MEMBERSHIP - STUDENTS LEARN TO FORM MEANINGFUL CONNECTIONS AND RELATIONSHIPS WITH PEERS AND ADULTS; AND CIVIC AND SOCIAL ABILITY - STUDENTS LEARN HOW TO WORK COLLABORATIVELY TO SUCCESSFULLY REACH A GOAL AND BELIEVE IN THEIR ABILITY TO HAVE AN IMPACT ON THEIR COMMUNITY AND SURROUNDINGS. CITYDANCE SEEKS TO ACHIEVE THESE GOALS THROUGH THE FOLLOWING ACTIVITIES: "DANCE INSTRUCTION: STUDENTS LEARN THE TECHNIQUE, HISTORY AND EVOLUTION OF A VARIETY OF DANCE FORMS. "COMMUNITY SERVICE: STUDENTS CHOOSE A COMMUNITY SERVICE PROJECT BY IDENTIFYING A COMMUNITY CONCERN AND CHOREOGRAPHING A DANCE TO ADDRESS THE CONCERN (E.G., HEALTHY EATING OR ANTI-DRUG CAMPAIGNS). "CREATIVE WRITING: THROUGH WEEKLY JOURNALING AND A PEN PAL PROGRAM WITH DREAM PARTICIPANTS AT DIFFERENT SCHOOLS, STUDENTS BUILD POSITIVE RELATIONSHIPS WITH PEERS AND HONE THEIR WRITING SKILLS. "DREAM PERFORMANCE REHEARSALS: DURING GROUP REHEARSALS WITH ALL DREAM PARTICIPANTS, STUDENTS LEARN THE VALUE OF TEAMWORK AND BRIDGING DIFFERENCES WHILE PRACTICING FOR THEIR MID-YEAR PERFORMANCE. "WIZARDS PERFORMANCE: STUDENTS PERFORM AT A WASHINGTON WIZARDS HALF-TIME SHOW AT THE VERIZON CENTER, EXPERIENCING THE THRILL OF PERFORMING FOR THE MORE THAN 20,000 PEOPLE IN ATTENDANCE. "ALL-SCHOOL ANNUAL PERFORMANCE: STUDENTS PERFORM IN A PROFESSIONAL THEATER FOR PARENTS AND COMMUNITY MEMBERS, SHOWCASING THEIR DANCE SKILLS AND THE COMMUNITY SERVICE PROJECTS THEY WORKED ON DURING THE YEAR. CITYDANCE ALSO BRINGS RENOWNED ARTISTS TO THE DC AREA THROUGH OUR ANNUAL GALA, WHICH RAISES FUNDS TO SUPPORT OUR CORNERSTONE COMMUNITY PROGRAM, DREAM. CO-PRODUCED BY RENOWNED DANCER AND PRODUCER RASTA THOMAS, THE EVENING BRINGS DANCE SUPERSTARS FROM AROUND THE WORLD FOR ONE NIGHT OF SPECTACULAR DANCE AT DC'S LINCOLN THEATRE. IN ADDITION TO PRESENTING NATIONALLY-RENOWNED ARTISTS THROUGH CITYDANCE ONSTAGE, WE ALSO PRESENT LOCAL ARTISTS THROUGH CITYDANCE IGNITE. THE PROGRAM SUPPORTS EMERGING DANCE ARTISTS IN THE CREATION AND PERFORMANCE OF THEIR WORK BY PROVIDING THEM WITH REHEARSAL SPACE IN THE SPACIOUS STUDIOS AT THE CITYDANCE CENTER AT STRATHMORE; THE ABILITY TO PRESENT THEIR ORIGINAL WORK IN THE STATE-OF-THE-ART CITYDANCE STUDIO THEATER AT STRATHMORE; AND MARKETING, PR, AND ADMINISTRATIVE SUPPORT FROM CITYDANCE STAFF. RESIDENT ARTISTS INCLUDED ROBERT J. PRIORE, ASANGA DOMASK, AND SARA J. EWING. IN JANUARY, WE PRESENTED THE FIRST OF THESE ARTISTS, ROBERT J. PRIORE, DURING TWO SOLD-OUT PERFORMANCES IN THE STUDIO THEATER. THE COMPELLING PROGRAM FEATURED GUEST ARTISTS FROM DAYTON CONTEMPORARY DANCE COMPANY PERFORMING PRIORE'S NEWEST WORK, AN ORIGINAL WORK SET ON CONSERVATORY STUDENTS, AND A THIRD WORK FEATURING CONSERVATORY STUDENTS ALONGSIDE PROFESSIONAL DANCERS. IN MARCH RESIDENT ARTIST ASANGA DOMASK, AN INTERNATIONALLY-RECOGNIZED SRI LANKAN TRADITIONAL AND FOLK DANCE PERFORMER WHO DIRECTS CITYDANCE'S SRI LANKAN DANCE PROGRAM, PARTNERED WITH MARYLAND CLASSICAL YOUTH ORCHESTRAS AND CITYDANCE STUDENTS TO PERFORM INTERPRETATIONS OF THE ICONIC SWANS FROM "SWAN LAKE." IN APRIL, RESIDENT ARTIST SARA J. EWING PREMIERED HER FULL-LENGTH WORK, TRAPPED HAPPINESS, IN THE CITYDANCE STUDIO THEATER. CITYDANCE COMMUNITY PROGRAMS SERVING UNDER-RESOURCED YOUTH IN WASHINGTON DC FOR NEARLY TWO DECADES, CITYDANCE'S COMMUNITY PROGRAMS HAVE DEVELOPED A STRONG REPUTATION FOR ENGAGING AND EMPOWERING YOUNG PEOPLE. THROUGH TWO DISTINCTIVE PROGRAMS, DREAM AND REACHDC, CITYDANCE COMMUNITY PROGRAMS ARE OFFERED AT OVER 30 COMMUNITY-BASED SITES IN THE REGION'S MOST UNDER-RESOURCED NEIGHBORHOODS PROVIDING FREE PERFORMANCES, IN-SCHOOL AND AFTER-SCHOOL PROGRAMS, AND SUMMER CAMPS TO OVER 5,000 STUDENTS EACH YEAR. DREAM AS THE ARTS BECOME LESS ACCESSIBLE IN OUR SCHOOLS, DREAM REACHES INTO OUR NEIGHBORHOODS, GIVING BACK TO OUR STUDENTS WHAT IS FUNDAMENTAL TO ANY CHILD'S FUTURE - EXPERIENCE AND PARTICIPATION IN THE ARTS. NOW IN ITS TENTH YEAR, THE FOUR-HOUR A WEEK AFTER-SCHOOL PROGRAM IS OFFERED TO 120 STUDENTS IN THIRD THROUGH EIGHTH GRADES AT SIX DC PUBLIC SCHOOLS AND EMPLOYS THE PRINCIPLES OF ADVANCING YOUTH DEVELOPMENT - A NATIONALLY-RECOGNIZED MODEL FOR INSTILLING YOUTH WITH THE SKILLS NECESSARY FOR SUCCESS IN LIFE. THE DREAM CURRICULUM IS DESIGNED TO ACHIEVE THREE SPECIFIC AYD GOALS: MASTERY AND FUTURE - STUDENTS DEVELOP A SENSE OF COMPETENCY AND THE BELIEF THEY CAN CREATE SUCCESS IN THEIR LIVES; BELONGING AND MEMBERSHIP - STUDENTS LEARN TO FORM MEANINGFUL CONNECTIONS AND RELATIONSHIPS WITH PEERS AND ADULTS; AND CIVIC AND SOCIAL ABILITY - STUDENTS LEARN HOW TO WORK COLLABORATIVELY TO SUCCESSFULLY REACH A GOAL AND BELIEVE IN THEIR ABILITY TO HAVE AN IMPACT ON THEIR COMMUNITY AND SURROUNDINGS. CITYDANCE SEEKS TO ACHIEVE THESE GOALS THROUGH THE FOLLOWING ACTIVITIES: "DANCE INSTRUCTION: STUDENTS LEARN THE TECHNIQUE, HISTORY AND EVOLUTION OF A VARIETY OF DANCE FORMS. "COMMUNITY SERVICE: STUDENTS CHOOSE A COMMUNITY SERVICE PROJECT BY IDENTIFYING A COMMUNITY CONCERN AND CHOREOGRAPHING A DANCE TO ADDRESS THE CONCERN (E.G., HEALTHY EATING OR ANTI-DRUG CAMPAIGNS). "CREATIVE WRITING: THROUGH WEEKLY JOURNALING AND A PEN PAL PROGRAM WITH DREAM PARTICIPANTS AT DIFFERENT SCHOOLS, STUDENTS BUILD POSITIVE RELATIONSHIPS WITH PEERS AND HONE THEIR WRITING SKILLS. "DREAM PERFORMANCE REHEARSALS: DURING GROUP REHEARSALS WITH ALL DREAM PARTICIPANTS, STUDENTS LEARN THE VALUE OF TEAMWORK AND BRIDGING DIFFERENCES WHILE PRACTICING FOR THEIR MID-YEAR PERFORMANCE. "WIZARDS PERFORMANCE: STUDENTS PERFORM AT A WASHINGTON WIZARDS HALF-TIME SHOW AT THE VERIZON CENTER, EXPERIENCING THE THRILL OF PERFORMING FOR THE MORE THAN 20,000 PEOPLE IN ATTENDANCE. "ALL-SCHOOL ANNUAL PERFORMANCE: STUDENTS PERFORM IN A PROFESSIONAL THEATER FOR PARENTS AND COMMUNITY MEMBERS, SHOWCASING THEIR DANCE SKILLS AND THE COMMUNITY SERVICE PROJECTS THEY WORKED ON DURING THE YEAR. "CULMINATING COMMUNITY PERFORMANCE: EACH DREAM SCHOOL HOSTS ITS OWN YEAR- END PERFORMANCE AT A VENUE RELEVANT TO THEIR COMMUNITY GOAL. WE ASSESS DREAM THROUGH FORMAL EVALUATION TOOLS DEVELOPED BY EXTERNAL EVALUATORS IN 2011 THAT UTILIZE QUALITATIVE AND QUANTITATIVE ASSESSMENT TOOLS SUCH AS FOCUS GROUPS, PRE- AND POST-TEST SKILLS ASSESSMENT SURVEYS FROM TEACHERS, AND PRE- AND POST-TEST SELF- ASSESSMENT SURVEYS. IN 2014, THESE SAME EVALUATORS REVIEWED DREAM AND CREATED NEW EVALUATION TOOLS THAT CAN BE USED BY CITYDANCE STAFF FOR YEARS TO COME, YOUTH SELF-ASSESSMENT TOOLS, KNOWLEDGE SURVEYS AND YEAR-END FEEDBACK SURVEYS. DUE TO HOW PROFOUNDLY DREAM CONSISTENTLY IMPACTS THE DC PUBLIC SCHOOL STUDENTS WE SERVE, WE BECAME DETERMINED TO DEEPEN AND LENGTHEN OUR RELATIONSHIP WITH THESE YOUTH. IN 2010, WE BEGAN OFFERING CONTINUED SERVICES TO STUDENTS FROM SIXTH GRADE THROUGH HIGH SCHOOL THROUGH OUR DREAM ALUMNI PROGRAM. TODAY, CITYDANCE SERVES 34 STUDENTS THROUGH THE PROGRAM GIVING THEM FREE DANCE INSTRUCTION FOR TWO HOURS EACH WEEK SEPTEMBER THROUGH MAY BUILD UPON THE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PRINCIPLES THAT SERVE AS THE CORNERSTONE OF THE DREAM CURRICULUM. ADDITIONALLY, WE PROVIDE ALUMNI WITH THE OPPORTUNITY TO SEE PROFESSIONAL DANCE PERFORMANCES FREE OF CHARGE, PERFORM ALONGSIDE DREAM STUDENTS AND IN THEIR OWN SHOWS, ACADEMIC TUTORING, THE OPTION TO MENTOR DREAM STUDENTS, AND HELP WITH COLLEGE PLANNING AND PREPARATION. REACHDC THROUGH PARTNERSHIPS WITH ORGANIZATIONS THROUGHOUT THE METROPOLITAN AREA, REACHDC EXPANDS CITYDANCE'S CONNECTION TO THE LARGER COMMUNITY. PROGRAMMING RANGES FROM PERFORMANCES IN A VAST ARRAY OF GENRES TO ARTS-INTEGRATION RESIDENCIES, SUMMER CAMPS, AFTER-SCHOOL PROGRAMS, AND FIELD-TRIPS. REACHDC PARTNERS INCLUDE: BOYS AND GIRLS CLUB, DC DEPARTMENT OF PARKS AND RECREATION, DC PUBLIC SCHOOLS, DEA YOUTH DANCE PROGRAM, KIPP DC CHARTER SCHOOLS, MONTGOMERY COUNTY DEPARTMENT OF RECREATION, THE SITAR ARTS CENTER, SPRINGBOARD AFTER SCHOOL, AND WASHINGTON PERFORMING ARTS SOCIETY. REACH DC PROVIDED THE FOLLOWING DANCE EDUCATION PROGRAMMING AND FREE PERFORMANCES: -CITYDANCE WILL HELD FREE PROFESSIONAL "DANCING IN ONE LANGUAGE" PERFORMANCES FOR OVER 1,500 STUDENTS ACROSS THE DC-METRO AREA. -SUMMER CAMPS: STEEPED IN THE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PHILOSOPHY, CITYDANCE'S DANCING AROUND THE WORLD SUMMER CAMPS PROVIDED SAFETY AND STRUCTURE FOR OVER 400 YOUTH. CAMPS WERE OFFERED TO YOUTH AGES 5 -14, FROM 4-8 WEEKS FOR SEVERAL HOURS A DAY AT SEVERAL COMMUNITY-BASED SITES, INCLUDING THE KIPP DC SCHOOLS, YMCA, THE BOYS AND GIRLS CLUB AND FOUR MARYLAND-BASED RECREATION CENTERS THROUGH A PARTNERSHIP WITH THE COMMONWEAL FOUNDATION. -AFTER-SCHOOL PARTNERSHIPS: THROUGH LONG-STANDING PARTNERSHIPS, CITYDANCE BRINGS DANCE INSTRUCTION TO COMMUNITY-BASED SITES AND SCHOOLS, PROVIDING WEEKLY INSTRUCTION IN A VARIETY OF GENRES TO OVER 200 STUDENTS. "CULMINATING COMMUNITY PERFORMANCE: EACH DREAM SCHOOL HOSTS ITS OWN YEAR- END PERFORMANCE AT A VENUE RELEVANT TO THEIR COMMUNITY GOAL. WE ASSESS DREAM THROUGH FORMAL EVALUATION TOOLS DEVELOPED BY EXTERNAL EVALUATORS IN 2011 THAT UTILIZE QUALITATIVE AND QUANTITATIVE ASSESSMENT TOOLS SUCH AS FOCUS GROUPS, PRE- AND POST-TEST SKILLS ASSESSMENT SURVEYS FROM TEACHERS, AND PRE- AND POST-TEST SELF- ASSESSMENT SURVEYS. IN 2014, THESE SAME EVALUATORS REVIEWED DREAM AND CREATED NEW EVALUATION TOOLS THAT CAN BE USED BY CITYDANCE STAFF FOR YEARS TO COME, YOUTH SELF-ASSESSMENT TOOLS, KNOWLEDGE SURVEYS AND YEAR-END FEEDBACK SURVEYS. DUE TO HOW PROFOUNDLY DREAM CONSISTENTLY IMPACTS THE DC PUBLIC SCHOOL STUDENTS WE SERVE, WE BECAME DETERMINED TO DEEPEN AND LENGTHEN OUR RELATIONSHIP WITH THESE YOUTH. IN 2010, WE BEGAN OFFERING CONTINUED SERVICES TO STUDENTS FROM SIXTH GRADE THROUGH HIGH SCHOOL THROUGH OUR DREAM ALUMNI PROGRAM. TODAY, CITYDANCE SERVES 34 STUDENTS THROUGH THE PROGRAM GIVING THEM FREE DANCE INSTRUCTION FOR TWO HOURS EACH WEEK SEPTEMBER THROUGH MAY BUILD UPON THE YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PRINCIPLES THAT SERVE AS THE CORNERSTONE OF THE DREAM CURRICULUM. ADDITIONALLY, WE PROVIDE ALUMNI WITH THE OPPORTUNITY TO SEE PROFESSIONAL DANCE PERFORMANCES FREE OF CHARGE, PERFORM ALONGSIDE DREAM STUDENTS AND IN THEIR OWN SHOWS, ACADEMIC TUTORING, THE OPTION TO MENTOR DREAM STUDENTS, AND HELP WITH COLLEGE PLANNING AND PREPARATION. REACHDC THROUGH PARTNERSHIPS WITH ORGANIZATIONS THROUGHOUT THE METROPOLITAN AREA, REACHDC EXPANDS CITYDANCE'S CONNECTION TO THE LARGER COMMUNITY. PROGRAMMING RANGES FROM PERFORMANCES IN A VAST ARRAY OF GENRES TO ARTS-INTEGRATION RESIDENCIES, SUMMER CAMPS, AFTER-SCHOOL PROGRAMS, AND FIELD-TRIPS. REACHDC PARTNERS INCLUDE: BOYS AND GIRLS CLUB, DC DEPARTMENT OF PARKS AND RECREATION, DC PUBLIC SCHOOLS, DEA YOUTH DANCE PROGRAM, KIPP DC CHARTER SCHOOLS, MONTGOMERY COUNTY DEPARTMENT OF RECREATION, THE SITAR ARTS CENTER, SPRINGBOARD AFTER SCHOOL, AND WASHINGTON PERFORMING ARTS SOCIETY. CAMPS WERE OFFERED TO YOUTH AGES 5 -14, FROM 4-8 WEEKS FOR SEVERAL HOURS A DAY AT SEVERAL COMMUNITY-BASED SITES, INCLUDING THE KIPP DC SCHOOLS, YMCA, THE BOYS AND GIRLS CLUB AND FOUR MARYLAND-BASED RECREATION CENTERS THROUGH A PARTNERSHIP WITH THE COMMONWEAL FOUNDATION. -AFTER-SCHOOL PARTNERSHIPS: THROUGH LONG-STANDING PARTNERSHIPS, CITYDANCE BRINGS DANCE INSTRUCTION TO COMMUNITY-BASED SITES AND SCHOOLS, PROVIDING WEEKLY INSTRUCTION IN A VARIETY OF GENRES TO OVER 200 STUDENTS. activityormissiondesc: DC SCORES builds teams through after-school programs for 1,500 low-income DC youth at 47 schools by instilling self-expression, physical fitness, and a sense of community.
desc: Elementary Program - Our holistic after-school program helps DC SCORES students improve their fitness levels by playing soccer; develop their literacy skills and capacity for self-expression by writing poetry; and establish deep community connections through service projects; all while developing closer bonds with teachers and peers. Our program follows a school-based model for after-school programming by hiring and training teachers (called our "SCORE Corps" coaches) from each school. Each school year, elementary and middle school students participate in over 24 weeks of programming. DC SCORES' elementary school program operates five days per week.

missiondesc: For people who believe in a well-rounded childhood, DC SCORES has a quality, team-based approach providing youth with the arts, athletics, and academics that will engage, enrich, and improve their lives. DC SCORES builds teams through after-school programs for 1,500 low-income DC youth at 47 schools by instilling self-expression, physical fitness, and a sense of community. DC SCORES accomplishes this in an innovative model combining poetry and spoken word, soccer, and service-learning year-round. We have worked with over 8,000 students since our founding in 1994 and we aim to serve EVERY child in the District deserving of a team who does not have one. DC SCORES is an affiliate of America SCORES, with organizations in 13 cities.

activityormissiondesc: UNITED PLANNING ORGANIZATION'S MISSION IS TO PLAN, COORDINATE & IMPLEMENT HUMAN SERVICES.
desc: HEAD START AND EARLY HEAD START - UPO'S COMPREHENSIVE PRESCHOOL AND DAY CARE NETWORK INCLUDES FIVE HEAD START DELEGATE AGENCIES, TEN EARLY CHILDHOOD DEVELOPMENT CENTERS (ECDCS) AND THREE OTHER NON-PROFIT CHILD CARE PROVIDERS THAT HAVE SERVICE AGREEMENTS. UPO'S HEAD START PROGRAM WAS INITIATED IN 1964 AND WAS ONE OF THE FIRST PILOT PROGRAMS IN THE COUNTRY. UPO CONTINUES TO SUPPORT A RAPIDLY EXPANDING HEAD START OPERATION AND IS ONE OF THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA'S LARGEST SERVICE PROVIDERS OF DAY CARE PROGRAMS. HEAD START AND EARLY HEAD START PROVIDES FAMILY DEVELOPMENT SERVICES AS WELL AS CHILD DEVELOPMENT AND SCHOOL READINESS SERVICES, HEALTH/MENTAL HEALTH SERVICES, NUTRITION SERVICES, AND DISABILITIES SERVICES TO CHILDREN AGES ZERO TO FIVE. PARENTS PARTICIPATE IN THE PARENT POLICY COUNCIL, PARENTING CLASSES AND AS CENTER VOLUNTEERS. COORDINATION AND LINKAGES TO OTHER UPO PRIVATE AND GOVERNMENTAL SUPPORT SERVICES ARE ALSO PROVIDED. UPO IS REQUIRED TO PROVIDE SERVICES TO 1,386 CHILDREN AGES THREE TO FIVE AND THEIR FAMILIES, 366 INFANTS/TODDLERS AND THEIR FAMILIES, AND PREGNANT WOMEN.

UPO CONTINUES TO SUPPORT A RAPIDLY EXPANDING HEAD START OPERATION AND IS ONE OF THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA'S LARGEST SERVICE PROVIDERS OF DAY CARE PROGRAMS. HEAD START AND EARLY HEAD START PROVIDES FAMILY DEVELOPMENT SERVICES AS WELL AS CHILD DEVELOPMENT AND SCHOOL READINESS SERVICES, HEALTH/MENTAL HEALTH SERVICES, NUTRITION SERVICES, AND DISABILITIES SERVICES TO CHILDREN AGES ZERO TO FIVE. PARENTS PARTICIPATE IN THE PARENT POLICY COUNCIL, PARENTING CLASSES AND AS CENTER VOLUNTEERS. COORDINATION AND LINKAGES TO OTHER UPO PRIVATE AND GOVERNMENTAL SUPPORT SERVICES ARE ALSO PROVIDED. UPO IS REQUIRED TO PROVIDE SERVICES TO 1,386 CHILDREN AGES THREE TO FIVE AND THEIR FAMILIES, 366 INFANTS/TODDLERS AND THEIR FAMILIES, AND PREGNANT WOMEN.

activityormissiondesc: PROVIDE OUT OF SCHOOL TIME EDUCATION FOR 5TH THROUGH 8TH GRADERS
desc: OUT OF SCHOOL TIME EDUCATIONPROVIDE AFTER SCHOOL AND SUMMER ACADEMIC ENRICHMENT IN UNDERSERVED AREAS OF WASHINGTON, DC, VIRGINIA, PENNSYLVANIA AND MARYLAND. HIGHER ACHIEVEMENT SERVES OVER 1,100 CHILDREN IN GRADES 5-8. SERVICES INCLUDE HOMEWORK HELP, ACTIVITIES, EVENING MEALS AND MENTORING THREE NIGHTS PER WEEK DURING THE ACADEMIC YEAR AND SIX WEEKS OF RIGOROUS ACADEMIC WORK DURING SUMMER. SUMMER ACADEMY IS EIGHT HOURS PER DAY FIVE DAYS PER WEEK AND INCLUDES TWO MEALS PER DAY. THE PROGRAM IS FREE TO THE FAMILIES. STUDENTS IMPROVE ON STANDARDIZED TESTS, GRADES, AND CONFIDENCE, AND ARE PLACED IN TOP HIGH SCHOOLS.

explanationtxt: HIGHER ACHIEVEMENT IS EXEMPT FROM FEDERAL INCOME TAX UNDER SECTION 501(C)(3) OF THE INTERNAL REVENUE CODE, EXCEPT ON NET INCOME FROM ACTIVITIES UNRELATED TO ITS EXEMPT PURPOSE. FOR THE YEARS ENDED AUGUST 31, 2014 AND 2013, NO ACCRUAL FOR BUSINESS INCOME TAXES WAS NECESSARY. HIGHER ACHIEVEMENT EVALUATED TAX POSITIONS AND DETERMINED THAT ITS POSITIONS ARE MORE LIKELY THAN NOT TO BE SUSTAINED ON EXAMINATION. HIGHER ACHIEVEMENT'S TAX RETURNS ARE SUBJECT TO REVIEW AND EXAMINATION BY FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES. THE BUSINESS INCOME TAX RETURNS FOR THE YEARS 2010, 2011, AND 2012 ARE OPEN TO EXAMINATION BY FEDERAL, LOCAL AND STATE AUTHORITIES.

activityormissiondesc: LSI is an educational program for students and teachers focusing on social and global leadership training and service learning trips to developing nations.
desc: LearnServe Abroad Program - the 8-month Abroad Program prepares students for 2-1/2 week summer service learning trips to Zambia, Paraguay, and Jamaica, with emphasis on social entrepreneurship, project planning, and leadership. Students continue their learning as they prepare public presentations to share with their communities, and action plans to support projects overseas. In the financial year ending June 30, 2014, 50 participants from 21 DC area schools traveled to Jamaica, Paraguay and Zambia. 65% of participants received financial aid for the program.

activityormissiondesc: THE MISSION OF MCIP AND ITS PUBLIC SCHOOL AFFILIATE, CHEC, IS TO STRIVE TO BECOME A MODEL PROFESSIONAL LEARNING COMMUNITY THAT RESPECTS AND RESPONDS TO THE DIVERSE NEEDS OF OUR UNDER-SERVED STUDENTS BY PREPARING THEM FOR THE ACADEMIC RIGORS OF COLLEGE AND AS LEADERS IN THE QUEST FOR SOCIAL JUSTICE. A PROFESSIONAL LEARNING COMMUNITY IS A COLLABORATIVE ACADEMIC ENVIRONMENT IN WHICH THE ADMINISTRATIVE STAFF AND TEACHERS IN A SCHOOL CONTINUOUSLY SEEK AND SHARE LEARNING AND THEN ACT ON WHAT THEY LEARN. THE GOAL IS TO ENHANCE THEIR EFFECTIVENESS AS PROFESSIONALS TO BENEFIT STUDENT EDUCATION. THE RESULTS OF THIS RESEARCH-BASED APPROACH IS THAT STUDENTS EXPERIENCE DECREASED DROPOUT RATE AND FEWER CLASSES "SKIPPED", LOWER RATES OF ABSENTEEISM, INCREASED LEARNING THAT IS DISTRIBUTED MORE EQUITABLY IN A SMALLER SIZED SCHOOL, GREATER ACADEMIC GAINS THAN IN TRADITIONAL SCHOOLS, AND SMALLER ACHIEVEMENT GAPS BETWEEN STUDENTS FROM DIFFERENT BACKGROUNDS.
desc: TEEN PARENT AND CHILD DEVELOPMENT CENTER - A NATIONAL ASSOCIATION FORTHE EDUCATION OF YOUNG CHILDREN (NAEYC) ACCREDITED PROGRAM THAT IS RUNBY A TEAM OF CERTIFIED EARLY CHILDHOOD EDUCATORS AND MAINTAINS A GOLDSTAR RATING, THE DISTRICTS HIGHEST EARLY CHILDHOOD CREDENTIAL. THECENTER'S STAFF MEETS THE NEEDS OF INFANTS, TODDLERS, AND THEIR TEENPARENTS BY PROVIDING COGNITIVE AGE-APPROPRIATE ACTIVITIES, CASEMANAGEMENT, AND PARENTING CLASSES FOR TEEN PARENTS. IN ADDITION TO THEDAILY PROVISION OF QUALITY CHILDCARE SERVICE AND TEEN PARENTINGSUPPORT, THE CENTER IS MISSIONED TO WORK WITH FATHERS AND GRANDPARENTSTO STRENGTHEN FAMILIES AND PROVIDE INTERGENERATIONAL PROGRAMMING.

missiondesc: THE MISSION OF MCIP AND ITS PUBLIC SCHOOL AFFILIATE, CHEC, IS TO STRIVE TO BECOME A MODEL PROFESSIONAL LEARNING COMMUNITY THAT RESPECTS AND RESPONDS TO THE DIVERSE NEEDS OF OUR UNDER-SERVED STUDENTS BY PREPARING THEM FOR THE ACADEMIC RIGORS OF COLLEGE AND AS LEADERS IN THE QUEST FOR SOCIAL JUSTICE. A PROFESSIONAL LEARNING COMMUNITY IS A COLLABORATIVE ACADEMIC ENVIRONMENT IN WHICH THE ADMINISTRATIVE STAFF AND TEACHERS IN A SCHOOL CONTINUOUSLY SEEK AND SHARE LEARNING AND THEN ACT ON WHAT THEY LEARN. THE GOAL IS TO ENHANCE THEIR EFFECTIVENESS AS PROFESSIONALS TO BENEFIT STUDENT EDUCATION. THE RESULTS OF THIS RESEARCH-BASED APPROACH IS THAT STUDENTS EXPERIENCE DECREASED DROPOUT RATE AND FEWER CLASSES "SKIPPED", LOWER RATES OF ABSENTEEISM, INCREASED LEARNING THAT IS DISTRIBUTED MORE EQUITABLY IN A SMALLER SIZED SCHOOL, GREATER ACADEMIC GAINS THAN IN TRADITIONAL SCHOOLS, AND SMALLER ACHIEVEMENT GAPS BETWEEN STUDENTS FROM DIFFERENT BACKGROUNDS.

activityormissiondesc: THE ORGANIZATION PARTNERS WITH SCHOOLS TO PROVIDE ONE-ON-ONE LITERACY TUTORING.
desc: LITERACY INTERVENTION PROGRAM: READING PARTNERS RECRUITS AND TRAINS COMMUNITY VOLUNTEERS TO PROVIDE ONE-ON-ONE TUTORING FOR STUDENTS BOTH DURING THE SCHOOL DAY AND AFTER SCHOOL. AT EACH PARTNERS SCHOOL, THE ORGANIZATION TAKES ON A DEDICATED SPACE, TRANSFORMS IT INTO A READING CENTER, AND PLACES A FULL TIME STAFF MEMBER ON SITE TO SUPERVISE ALL PROGRAM SERVICES AND SERVE AS THE LIAISON TO CLASSROOM TEACHERS. A TYPICAL READING CENTER WILL SERVE BETWEEN 30 AND 90 STUDENTS.THE PRIMARY PROGRAM COMPONENT, ONE-ON-ONE TUTORING, IS SUPPLEMENTED WITH PARENT AND FAMILY INVOLVEMENT. STUDENTS ENROLLED IN THE READING PARTNERS PROGRAM ARE SEEN TWICE PER WEEK FOR 45-MINUTE ONE-ON-ONE TUTORING SESSIONS WITH TRAINED COMMUNITY VOLUNTEERS. EACH SESSION IS COMPRISED OF A HIGHLY STRUCTURED, RESEARCH-BASED CURRICULUM WHICH ALLOWS VOLUNTEERS WITH LITTLE BACKGROUND IN EDUCATION TO BE EFFECTIVE TUTORS.

explanationtxt: AS DETERMINED BY THE INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE (IRS), READING PARTNERS IS EXEMPT FROM FEDERAL INCOME TAXES UNDER SECTION 501(C)(3) OF THE INTERNAL REVENUE CODE AND EXEMPT FROM STATE INCOME TAXES UNDER VARIOUS STATE CODES AND STATUTES OF CALIFORNIA, WASHINGTON, D.C., NEW YORK, MARYLAND, TEXAS, COLORADO, NORTH CAROLINA, MASSACHUSETTS, SOUTH CAROLINA AND OKLAHOMA. ACCORDINGLY, NO PROVISION FOR INCOME TAXES HAS BEEN MADE IN THE ACCOMPANYING STATEMENTS. EACH YEAR, MANAGEMENT CONSIDERS WHETHER ANY MATERIAL TAX POSITION READING PARTNERS HAS TAKEN IS MORE LIKELY THAN NOT TO BE SUSTAINED UPON EXAMINATION BY THE APPLICABLE TAX AUTHORITY. MANAGEMENT BELIEVES THAT ANY POSITIONS THE ORGANIZATION HAS TAKEN ARE SUPPORTED BY SUBSTANTIAL AUTHORITY AND, HENCE, DO NOT NEED TO BE MEASURED OR DISCLOSED IN THESE FINANCIAL STATEMENTS. TAX RETURNS FOR YEARS SUBSEQUENT TO JUNE 2010 ARE SUBJECT TO EXAMINATION BY FEDERAL OR STATE TAX AUTHORITIES.

activityormissiondesc: The Best Friends Foundation provides an educational curriculum and/or group assemblies in the Metropolitan Washington DC area for adolescent girls and boys, Aged 10-18, which promotes self-respect through the practice self-control by providing skills and guidance which help them avoid risk behavior.The five basic goals of the Best Friends / Best Men program are:1. To develop critical thinking skills in adolescent girls and boys to enable them to progress from the concrete to the formal operational stage of reasoning.2. To develop a sense of self-respect and self-worth through achievement and community service.3. To enrich the lives of adolescent girls and boys by promoting their aspirations and providing decision-making skills.4. To incorporate the school and families into the adolescent girls' and boys' support system.5. To provide positive peer groups for 10-18 year old girls in which they are valued members and in which they have a sense of connection to their school and to each oth
desc: Metropolitan Best Friends, Diamond Girl Leadership, Best Men and Best Men Leadership Programs provides participants with curriculum discussions and role model presentations. Seminars such as Health is Happiness, Health is Fitness, Make Music Not Madness, Stop the Silence, Prevent the Violence are offered to students, teachers, and parents. The program teaches decision making skills which avoid risk behaviors, and it promotes character building activities for peer groups.

activityormissiondesc: FDIA provides opportunity, education, and inspiration to young people in DC area through ice skating & educational activities. Activities include public skating, lessons, and availability of facilities for teams and schools. FDIA provides a safe place for young people with structured activities.
desc: FDIA provides instructional skating to school-age children from the nearby neighborhood, including programs with approximately 50 public schools. Regular skating lessons and class opportunities are provided to the general public and members of the community. In addition, the arena is provided to allow for practice and games for university, high school, and league hockey teams.

INCOME TAX BENEFITS ARE RECOGNIZED FOR INCOME TAX POSITIONS TAKEN OR EXPECTED TO BE TAKEN IN A TAX RETURN, ONLY WHEN IT IS DETERMINED THAT THE INCOME TAX POSITION WILL MORE-LIKELY-THAN-NOT BE SUSTAINED UPON EXAMINATION BY TAXING AUTHORITIES. THE CENTER HAS ANALYZED TAX POSITIONS TAKEN FOR FILING WITH THE INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE AND ALL STATE JURISDICTIONS WHERE IT OPERATES. THE CENTER BELIEVES THAT INCOME TAX FILING POSITIONS WILL BE SUSTAINED UPON EXAMINATION AND DOES NOT ANTICIPATE ANY ADJUSTMENTS THAT WOULD RESULT IN A MATERIAL ADVERSE EFFECT ON THE CENTER'S FINANCIAL POSITION, RESULTS OF ACTIVITIES OR CASH FLOWS. ACCORDINGLY, THE CENTER HAS NOT RECORDED ANY RESERVES, OR RELATED ACCRUALS FOR INTEREST AND PENALTIES FOR UNCERTAIN TAX POSITIONS AT JUNE 30, 2014. THE CENTER IS STILL OPEN TO EXAMINATION BY TAXING AUTHORITIES FROM 2011 FORWARD.

THE CENTER BELIEVES THAT INCOME TAX FILING POSITIONS WILL BE SUSTAINED UPON EXAMINATION AND DOES NOT ANTICIPATE ANY ADJUSTMENTS THAT WOULD RESULT IN A MATERIAL ADVERSE EFFECT ON THE CENTER'S FINANCIAL POSITION, RESULTS OF ACTIVITIES OR CASH FLOWS. ACCORDINGLY, THE CENTER HAS NOT RECORDED ANY RESERVES, OR RELATED ACCRUALS FOR INTEREST AND PENALTIES FOR UNCERTAIN TAX POSITIONS AT JUNE 30, 2014. THE CENTER IS STILL OPEN TO EXAMINATION BY TAXING AUTHORITIES FROM 2011 FORWARD.

desc: CYIT: CHILDREN AND YOUTH INVESTMENT TRUST CORPORATION THE DC CHILDREN AND YOUTH INVESTMENT TRUST CORPORATION (THE TRUST) IS A PUBLIC PRIVATE PARTNERSHIP CHARTERED BY THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA TO HELP A WIDE VARIETY OF ORGANIZATIONS IMPROVE THE QUALITY, QUANTITY AND ACCESSIBILITY OF SERVICES AND OPPORTUNITIES FOR EVERY CHILD IN THE CITY. THE TRUST WORKS TO INCREASE RESOURCES AND INVEST IN THE PEOPLE, PROGRAMS, AND SYSTEMS THAT SERVE CHILDREN, YOUTH, AND THEIR FAMILIES IN THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA. THE DC CHILDREN AND YOUTH INVESTMENT TRUST CORPORATION (THE TRUST) IS THE PRIMARY RESOURCE FOR DEVELOPING PARTNERSHIPS THAT EXPAND AND IMPROVE SERVICES AND OPPORTUNITIES FOR CHILDREN AND YOUTH IN THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA, ESPECIALLY DURING THEIR TIME OUT OF SCHOOL. THE PARTNERSHIPS INCLUDE THOSE WITH PUBLIC SCHOOLS, CITY AGENCIES, NONPROFIT PROVIDERS AND FUNDERS. THE TRUST PROVIDES GRANTS, TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE, YOUTH WORKER TRAINING, CAPACITY BUILDING, LEARNING OPPORTUNITIES, AND POLICY SUPPORT IN THE DISTRICT. THE TRUST SUPPORTS AND DEVELOPS THE HIGHEST QUALITY PROGRAMS, ENCOURAGES INNOVATION IN SERVICES AND ORGANIZATIONS, AND INVESTS IN ACTIVITIES THAT WILL CREATE BETTER OUTCOMES FOR DC'S CHILDREN AND YOUTH.

activityormissiondesc: YOUTH DEVELOPMENT PROGRAM FOR BOYS AND YOUNG MEN LIVING IN LOW-INCOME AND PUBLIC HOUSING.
desc: THE ARTS/CREATIVE EXPRESSION PROGRAM IS DESIGNED SPECIFICALLY TO ENGAGE APPRENTICES ON A WEEKLY BASIS IN OUR CREATIVE PROCESS: CONNECTING, CREATING, CONTRIBUTING AND CELEBRATING. THE PROGRAM GUIDES APPRENTICES TO CHANNEL THEIR LIFE EXPERIENCES USING THE CREATION OF ACRYLIC COLLAGE PAINTINGS, ORIGINAL POETRY, PROSE, ORATORY, MOVEMENT/DANCE, AND MUSIC. THE CREATIONS ARE THEN SHARED WITH A BROADER AUDIENCE. THIS PROGRAM CONTINUES TO STRENGTHEN AS WE ADD NEW ARTISTS WHO BRING THEIR OWN UNIQUE ARTISTIC STYLES TO THE EXPERIENCE.THE ACADEMIC/EDUCATION PROGRAM ENGAGES ALL APPRENTICES IN RIGOROUS HOMEWORK ASSISTANCE, TUTORING, LITERACY TRAINING, MATH SKILL DEVELOPMENT, AND COMPUTER TRAINING ON A DAILY BASIS.WE ALSO OFFER OUR APPRENTICES:-EDUCATION AND WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT TRAINING THROUGH LIFE PIECES ART WORKS-LEADERSHIP DEVELOPMENT-ACADEMIC ENRICHMENT THROUGH EXTRA-CURRICULAR ACTIVITIES-EXPOSURE TO OTHER CULTURES AND A GLOBAL COMMUNITY-AWARENESS OF AND EXPOSURE TO DIVERSE SPIRITUAL PRACTICES-HEALTH EDUCATION TO ENHANCE FITNESS, HEALTH, AND WELLNESSTOGETHER, ALL OF THESE PROGRAMS WILL SERVE AS A FOUNDATION FOR A SUCCESSFUL LEARNING EXPERIENCE AND TRANSITION TO PRODUCTIVE ADULTHOOD FOR OUR APPRENTICES.ADDITIONALLY, LPTM HAS FACILITATED WORKSHOPS AND TRAININGS WITH LOCAL NON-PROFITS, TEACHERS AT DREW ELEMENTARY SCHOOL AND THE BISHOP JOHN T. WALKER SCHOOL FOR BOYS, THE WORLD BANK GROUP, HOMELESS CHILDREN PLAYTIME PROJECT, DC PROMISE NEIGHBORHOOD INITIATIVE AND CONFERENCES HOSTED BY THE COALITION OF SCHOOLS EDUCATING BOYS OF COLOR (COSEBOC), THE COLLEGE BOARD, AND OTHERS. THROUGH OUR COLOR ME COMMUNITY CONVERSATIONS SERIES, OUR SKILLED TEAM OF TRAINERS BUILDS DISCUSSION WITH DC COMMUNITY MEMBERS FROM ALL BACKGROUNDS AROUND THE IMPLICATIONS OF RACE, GENER, CULTURAL BACKGROUND, AND OTHER FORMS OF IDENTITY IN OUR COMMUNITIES.

missiondesc: LIFE PIECES TO MASTERPIECES HAS IDENTIFIED EFFECTIVE, INNOVATIVE, AND REPLICABLE STRATEGIES THAT HAVE RESULTED IN A DRAMATIC IMPROVEMENT OF THE EARLY CHILDHOOD AND YOUTH DEVELOPMENT EXPERIENCES OF YOUNG, UNDERSERVED, AFRICAN AMERICAN MALES LIVING IN OUR NATION'S CAPITAL. activityormissiondesc: TO EMPOWER GIRLS TO REALIZE THEIR DREAMS THROUGH SCIENCE, TECHNOLOGY, AND ENGINEERING.
desc: AFTER-SCHOOL AND SUMMER PROGRAMSTECHBRIDGE'S AFTER-SCHOOL AND SUMMER PROGRAMS INSPIRE GIRLS IN GRADES 5-12 FROM UNDERSERVED COMMUNITIES IN SCIENCE, TECHNOLOGY AND ENGINEERING, PROVIDING GIRLS WITH HANDS-ON PROJECTS AND CAREER EXPLORATION THROUGH OUR CURRICULUM, ROLE MODELS, AND FIELD TRIPS. TECHBRIDGE'S HOLISTIC APPROACH GIVES GIRLS A STRONG SUPPORT NETWORK THROUGH TRAININGS AND RESOURCES OFFERED TO TEACHERS, FAMILIES, AND ROLE MODELS. TECHBRIDGE SERVED 14 SCHOOLS IN THE BAY AREA, AND BEGAN LAUNCHING OPERATIONS IN GREATER SEATTLE. EVALUATION RESULTS SHOW THAT 96% OF GIRLS THINK ENGINEERING IS A GOOD CAREER FOR WOMEN AND 98% OF PARENTS CITE AN INCREASE IN THEIR DAUGHTER'S CONFIDENCE IN STEM.
